name: 4-fluoroacetophenone
Reason: The compound 4-fluoroacetophenone consists of a benzene ring as its base unit (Phenol: +41°C) with two substituents: a fluoro group and an acetyl (carbonyl) group. The fluoro group is generally electron-withdrawing and tends to slightly lower the melting point due to its electronegative nature, which can weaken the crystal lattice (-5°C). The acetyl (carbonyl) group, however, is a polar functional group that, through its ability to accept hydrogen bonds, significantly raises the melting point (+20°C). Combining these effects leads to an overall expected increase in the melting point relative to the base phenol molecule.
